*SB0025.2*
January 27, 2026
SENATE BILL No. 25
_____
DIGEST OF SB 25 (Updated January 27, 2026 9:32 am - DI 149)
Citations Affected: IC 3-11.
Synopsis: School board candidates. Specifies that if there is more than
one candidate for a school board office within certain designated
groups of candidates, the candidates shall appear in a certain order and
within the grouping and in alphabetical order according to surname.
Effective: Upon passage.
Byrne, Gaskill
December 8, 2025, read first time and referred to Committee on Rules and Legislative
Procedure.
January 22, 2026, amended; reassigned to Committee on Elections.
January 27, 2026, reported favorably — Do Pass.
SB 25—LS 6039/DI 13

January 27, 2026
Second Regular Session of the 124th General Assembly (2026)
PRINTING CODE. Amendments: Whenever an existing statute (or a section of the Indiana
Constitution) is being amended, the text of the existing provision will appear in this style type,
additions will appear in this style type, and deletions will appear in this style type.
Additions: Whenever a new statutory provision is being enacted (or a new constitutional
provision adopted), the text of the new provision will appear in this style type. Also, the
word NEW will appear in that style type in the introductory clause of each SECTION that adds
a new provision to the Indiana Code or the Indiana Constitution.
Conflict reconciliation: Text in a statute in this style type or this style type reconciles conflicts
between statutes enacted by the 2025 Regular Session of the General Assembly.
SENATE BILL No. 25
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
elections.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 3-11-2-6, AS AMENDED BY P.L.11-2023,
2 SECTION 8, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 UPON PASSAGE]: Sec. 6. (a) The device named and list of nominees
4 shall be placed on the ballots as follows:
5 (1) The major political party whose candidate received the highest
6 number of votes in the county for secretary of state at the last
7 election in the first column or row on the left side of all ballots.
8 (2) The major political party whose candidate received the second
9 highest number of votes in the county for secretary of state at the
10 last election in the second column or row.
11 (3) Any other political party in the same order.
12 (b) If a political party did not have a candidate for secretary of state
13 in the last election or a nominee is an independent candidate (or an
14 independent ticket for President and Vice President of the United
15 States or for governor and lieutenant governor), the party or
16 independent candidate or ticket shall be placed on the ballot after the
17 parties described in subsection (a). If more than one (1) political party
SB 25—LS 6039/DI 13

2
1 or independent candidate or ticket that has qualified to be on the ballot
2 did not have a candidate for secretary of state in the last election, those
3 parties, candidates, or tickets shall be listed on the ballot in the order
4 in which the party filed its petition of nomination under IC 3-8-6-12.
5 (c) Subject to subsection (e), a column or row for write-in voting
6 shall be placed to the right of all party and independent columns on the
7 ballot.
8 (d) This subsection applies to a county having a population of more
9 than four hundred thousand (400,000) and less than seven hundred
10 thousand (700,000). If there is insufficient room on a row to list each
11 candidate of a political party, a second or subsequent row may be
12 utilized. However, a second or subsequent row may not be utilized
13 unless the first row, and all preceding rows, have been filled.
14 (e) A column or row for write-in voting for an office is not required
15 if there are no declared write-in candidates for that office. However,
16 procedures must be implemented to permit write-in voting for
17 candidates for federal offices.
18 (f) This subsection applies to candidates who appear on the
19 ballot for a school board office. The names of the candidates for
20 each office must be grouped together in the following order:
21 (1) The major political party whose candidate received the
22 highest number of votes in the county for secretary of state at
23 the last election is listed first.
24 (2) The major political party whose candidate received the
25 second highest number of votes in the county for secretary of
26 state is listed second.
27 (3) All other political parties listed in the order that the
28 parties' candidates for secretary of state finished in the last
29 election are listed after the party listed in subdivision (2).
30 (4) If a political party did not have a candidate for secretary
31 of state in the last election or a nominee is an independent
32 candidate, the party or candidate is listed after the parties
33 described in subdivisions (1), (2), and (3).
34 (5) If more than one (1) political party or independent
35 candidate qualifies to be on the ballot, the parties, candidates,
36 or tickets are listed in the order in which the party filed its
37 petition of nomination under IC 3-8-6-12.
38 (6) The name of a candidate described in
39 IC 3-8-2.5-2.5(a)(5)(C) is placed after the candidates listed in
40 subdivisions (1) through (5), if applicable.
41 (7) A space for write-in voting is placed after the candidates
42 listed in subdivisions (1) through (6), if required by law.
SB 25—LS 6039/DI 13

3
1 (8) The name of a write-in candidate may not be listed on the
2 ballot.
3 If there is more than one (1) candidate for a grouping described in
4 subdivisions (1) through (8) for a school board office, the
5 candidates shall appear in the order established by this subsection
6 and within the grouping, in alphabetical order according to
7 surname.
8 SECTION 2. IC 3-11-13-11, AS AMENDED BY THE
9 TECHNICAL CORRECTIONS BILL OF THE 2026 GENERAL
10 ASSEMBLY, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
11 UPON PASSAGE]: Sec. 11. (a) The ballot information, whether placed
12 on the ballot card or on the marking device, must be in the order of
13 arrangement provided for ballots under this section.
14 (b) Each county election board shall have the names of all
15 candidates for all elected offices, political party offices, and public
16 questions printed on a ballot card as provided in this chapter. The
17 county may:
18 (1) print all offices and questions on a single ballot card; and
19 (2) include a ballot variation code to ensure that the proper
20 version of a ballot is used within a precinct.
21 (c) Each type of ballot card must be of uniform size and of the same
22 quality and color of paper (except as permitted under IC 3-10-1-17).
23 (d) The nominees of a political party or an independent candidate
24 or independent ticket (described in IC 3-11-2-6) nominated by
25 petitioners shall be listed on the ballot with the name and device set
26 forth on the certification or petition. The circle containing the device
27 may be of any size that permits a voter to readily identify the device.
28 IC 3-11-2-5 applies if the certification or petition does not include a
29 name or device, or if the same device is selected by two (2) or more
30 parties or petitioners. In the case of a candidate described in
31 IC 3-8-2.5-2.5(a)(5)(C), a blank space must be printed after the
32 candidate's name signifying that the candidate elects not to disclose any
33 affiliation with a political party or that the candidate:
34 (1) is not affiliated with a political party; and
35 (2) does not identify as an independent candidate.
36 (e) The offices and public questions on the general election ballot
37 must be placed on the ballot in the order listed in IC 3-11-2-12,
38 IC 3-11-2-12.4, IC 3-11-2-12.5, IC 3-11-2-12.7(b), IC 3-11-2-12.9(a),
39 IC 3-11-2-12.9(c), IC 3-11-2-13(a) through IC 3-11-2-13(c),
40 IC 3-11-2-14(a), IC 3-11-2-14(d), and IC 3-11-2-14(e). The offices and
41 public questions may be listed in a continuous column either vertically
42 or horizontally and on a number of separate pages.
SB 25—LS 6039/DI 13

